Welcome Home, Rich!  Like you I encourage all who haven't been, to go get the advice and counseling that a Vet Center offers.  It's been 11 years since I went and it enabled me to put my service into the context that I could understand and live with.  It never &quot;cured&quot; me of PTSD, it just made me aware of it and how to cope with it.  How to adjust my survival skills (learned in-country) to coping skills.  It put some grays into my life.  Not everything is black and white anymore.  Not everything requires a decision that might cost people their lives and that has to be made in 5 seconds or less.  It is not necessary to be the biggest, baddest, m**f in the valley for people to respect you.  It is o.k. to realize that I did the best job that I could do for an 18 year old boy that was a squad leader.  It was o.k. to accept the fact that what I did in country was valuable and honorable.  <br>
Dixie, seek the understanding that other vets can provide.  The Vet Center is a valuable resource.  It is staffed by vets who have &quot;walked the walk&quot; so they CAN &quot;talk the talk&quot;.<br>
Rich, like you it took me a long time to realize that I needed help.  That old refrain from the sixties keeps coming back to haunt me. &quot;Sometimes the lights all shining on me...Sometimes I can barely see...Lately it occurs to me...What a long strange trip it's been&quot;<br>
Chet Botkins<br>
1st. Cav. 3/18th Arty  10/65 - 5/67<br>
&quot;You can't be first..But you can be next&quot;
